title: Battery Place - Washington Street, looking northeast

text:
(1) Battery Place, north side, east from Washington (left) to Greenwich Streets (right). Note the Battery Place station of the Sixth and Ninth Aves. Elevated Lines on Greenwich Street. The only building of this structure, the corner buildings being (left) No. 1 ½ Washington Street, No. 3-story, and No. 2 Greenwich Street, a 4-story affair. Shown on the left, on Washington Street, are Nos. 1 ½, 3-5, 7 and 9, at, adjoining and north of the N.E. corner of Battery Place. April 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) A closer view, showing in the foreground the N.E. corner of Washington Street and Battery Place. April 1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3) A view similar to No. 1, several years later. October 1928.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(4) The same as No. 1 and 3. On the extreme right appears a portion of the Washington Building, at the N.E. corner of Greenwich Street. May 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Washington Street, north from a point between Battery Place and Morris Street (seen in the foreground) and showing a view northeastward across Manhattan Syrian sector as viewed from the Whitehall Bldg. In the foreground appears a portion of the steel frame work of the Downtown Athletic Club. Shortly the adjacent rookeries will supplanted by the United Fruit Co. Bldg. In the center and to the left of the Singer Tower is the 23 storied Electric Bond and Share Bldg. at Rector Street.

June 20, 1929.

Washington Street, west side, north from, but not including Battery Place, to and including Morris Street. Buildings shown face onto West Street, and are from left to right, the Whitehall Building (No. 1-14), the Downtown Athletic Club (No. 18), and No. 21 respectively. The background shows piers and wharfs abutting onto the Hudson River.

About 1931.

Ewing Galloway.

Washington Street, west side, north from Battery Place to Morris Street, as seen across Battery Park. On the left, is the Whitehall Building (No. 1-14 West Street). Building bearing flag, is the Downtown Athletic Club (No. 18 West Street).

About 1931.
